<DocsLayout title="Architecture" description="ostk architecture: a single Rust binary kernel, FCP drivers for domain intelligence, and a daemon that coordinates agent fleets.">
  <p>ostk is a single binary that coordinates AI agents working on a codebase. Three layers: the kernel, the daemon, and drivers.</p>

  <h2>The kernel</h2>
  <p>A single Rust binary. Statically linked. No runtime dependencies. Seven primitives built on Unix-inspired filesystem operations. The kernel handles:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Write tracking</strong> &mdash; every file write is intercepted and assigned a generation counter via optimistic concurrency control</li>
    <li><strong>Conflict resolution</strong> &mdash; when two agents edit the same file, the kernel detects and resolves via Hot PR (three tiers: auto-merge, mechanical rebase, manual)</li>
    <li><strong>Output compression</strong> &mdash; three-tier pipeline strips ANSI, deduplicates lines, and classifies tool output. ~80% token savings. See <a href="/docs/compression">Compression</a></li>
    <li><strong>Capability enforcement</strong> &mdash; deny-based <a href="/docs/pins">pins</a> at the tool layer, process-level sandboxing via Landlock/Seatbelt at the syscall layer</li>
    <li><strong>Audit trail</strong> &mdash; every agent action is an append-only audit event. The process table is <code>fold(audit.jsonl)</code> &mdash; replaying the log reconstructs the fleet</li>
    <li><strong>Secret mediation</strong> &mdash; API keys resolved from keychain at call time, never stored in agent context</li>
    <li><strong>Fleet coordination</strong> &mdash; agent lifecycle (spawn, drain, reap, rehydrate), heartbeat crash detection, session topology, sub-stack isolation</li>
    <li><strong>Dangerous command detection</strong> &mdash; 14 pattern detectors scan every shell command for destructive operations before the agent sees the output</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The kernel boots from the <code>.ostk/</code> directory. It reads governance documents (HUMANFILE, ENTITYFILE), resolves trust tier, and begins tracking. No config needed beyond <code>ostk init</code> and <code>ostk boot</code>. See <a href="/docs/kernel-spec">Kernel Specification</a> for the full seven-primitive model.</p>

  <h2>The daemon</h2>
  <p><code>ostk listen</code> starts the kernel daemon &mdash; a long-lived anchor process that holds the socket, the process table, and the scheduler. The daemon is the coordination hub for multi-agent work:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Session management</strong> &mdash; agents run as managed sessions inside the daemon. Each session has its own context, heartbeat, and drain snapshot.</li>
    <li><strong>Scheduler tick loop</strong> &mdash; a background task that wakes the scheduler agent on a timer. The scheduler inspects fleet state and dispatches work (spawn workers, nudge agents, reap dead sessions).</li>
    <li><strong>Crash recovery</strong> &mdash; drain snapshots written at every turn boundary (default ON). On daemon restart, <code>fold(audit.jsonl)</code> reconstructs the fleet and rehydrates sessions from snapshots. Mid-flight: heartbeat monitor detects crashed workers and hot-rehydrates them without a restart.</li>
    <li><strong>Client multiplexing</strong> &mdash; TUI, MCP clients, CLI one-shots, and IDE extensions attach and detach from the daemon via the kernel socket. Agent sessions continue running regardless of client lifecycle.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The daemon is a cache, not a ledger. The source of truth is the filesystem &mdash; <code>audit.jsonl</code>, <code>gen_table.jsonl</code>, drain snapshots. A daemon restart reconstructs identical state from disk. See <a href="/docs/session-topology">Session Topology</a>.</p>

  <h2>Write interception</h2>
  <p>
    ostk intercepts writes at the <strong>tool layer</strong>, not the filesystem. There is no FUSE mount, no <code>inotify</code> watcher, no <code>LD_PRELOAD</code> shim, and no <code>ptrace</code> syscall interception. Agents write files through kernel-provided primitives (<code>file:edit</code>, <code>file:write</code>, <code>file:create</code>) that apply policy, locking, and version tracking before bytes hit disk.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is a deliberate trade-off. Filesystem-level interception provides universal coverage but at the cost of platform fragility and performance overhead. Tool-layer mediation covers only writes that go through the kernel&rsquo;s primitives, but with zero overhead for unmediated I/O, no platform-specific modules, and deterministic behavior: if a write went through the tool, the kernel saw it.
  </p>

  <h2>FCP drivers</h2>
  <p>Drivers extend the kernel with domain capabilities. They follow the FCP (File Context Protocol) interface &mdash; MCP servers that let LLMs interact with complex file formats and domain-specific operations through a verb-based DSL.</p>

  <h3>Internal drivers (ship with the kernel binary)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Driver</th><th>What it provides</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>fcp-screen</code></td>
        <td>TUI rendering &mdash; fleet status, work queue, permission modals, real-time agent output</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>fcp-web</code></td>
        <td>Web page reading &mdash; fetch, render, and extract content from URLs for agent consumption</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>fcp-llm</code></td>
        <td>LLM inference abstraction &mdash; CpuDriver trait, provider routing (Anthropic, Gemini, Mistral, OpenRouter)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

