  <p>Build your own drivers with the shared framework: <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/fcp-core" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">fcp-core</a> (TypeScript + Python) or <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/fcp-core-rust" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">fcp-core-rust</a> (Rust).</p>

  <p>Drivers are declared in your <a href="/docs/humanfile">HUMANFILE</a>:</p>
  <pre><code>DRIVER fcp-rust
DRIVER fcp-python
DRIVER fcp-pdf</code></pre>
  <p>The kernel loads them at boot. If a driver binary isn&rsquo;t found, the kernel skips it and logs a warning. Drivers are optional &mdash; the kernel works without any.</p>

  <h2>What the operator sees</h2>
  <p>From the operator&rsquo;s perspective, ostk is one command (<code>ostk</code>) that does everything. The kernel/daemon/driver split is invisible at the CLI level. You run <code>ostk</code> &mdash; fcp-screen handles rendering. You run <code>ostk listen</code> &mdash; the daemon starts. You run <code>ostk kernel spawn</code> &mdash; a worker appears. You never address a driver directly.</p>

  <h2>State layout</h2>
  <p>All OS state lives in the <code>.ostk/</code> directory at your project root:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Path</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/HUMANFILE</code></td><td>Operator identity and configuration</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/ENTITYFILE</code></td><td>Trust tiers and key registry</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/audit.jsonl</code></td><td>Append-only audit trail &mdash; the source of truth for fleet state</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/gen_table.jsonl</code></td><td>Generation counters for OCC &mdash; version vector per tracked file</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/.language</code></td><td>Syscall table &mdash; verb definitions, momentum, resolution routes</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/drain/</code></td><td>Drain snapshots &mdash; per-session state for crash recovery</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/pins/</code></td><td>Capability pin definitions &mdash; per-pin deny token sets (<code>pins/default/pin.caps</code>)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/needles/</code></td><td>Work items &mdash; the executable work queue</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/stacks/</code></td><td>Sub-stack isolation boundaries &mdash; scoped audit, drain, IPC per stack</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/boot.md</code></td><td>Boot state &mdash; compacted session context read at agent start</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>.ostk/anchor.lock</code></td><td>Single-anchor flock &mdash; guarantees one daemon per project root</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

